# PowerShell Scripting Standards

## Code Quality & Syntax Rules

### Function Naming
- Use approved PowerShell verbs: Get-, Set-, New-, Remove-, Test-, Invoke-, Add-, Clear-, Copy-, Move-, Rename-, Start-, Stop-, Restart-, Resume-, Suspend-
- Never use unapproved verbs like "Generate", "Process", "Create" - use "New-", "Invoke-", "Test-" instead
- Function names must follow Verb-Noun pattern: `New-AtlasJson`, not `Generate-AtlasJson`

### Parameter Validation
- Always use `[Parameter(Mandatory=$true)]` for required parameters
- Include parameter help with `[string]$Description = "Description"`
- Use proper parameter types: `[string]`, `[int]`, `[switch]`, `[array]`
- Validate input ranges: `[ValidateRange(1, 100)]` for counts, `[ValidateSet("16x16", "32x32")]` for enums

### Error Handling
- Use try-catch blocks for all operations that can fail
- Include specific error messages: `Write-Error "Failed to create directory: $($_.Exception.Message)"`
- Use `-ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` for non-critical operations
- Always check return values and handle failures gracefully

### Output Standards
- Use consistent status reporting with timestamps: `[HH:mm:ss] Message`
- Color-code output: Red=Error, Yellow=Warning, Green=Success, White=Info
- Include progress indicators: `✓` for success, `✗` for failure
- Provide actionable error messages with next steps

### Resource Management
- Always dispose of .NET objects: `$graphics.Dispose()`, `$bitmap.Dispose()`
- Use `try-finally` blocks for cleanup
- Check for null objects before disposal
- Use `using` statements for automatic disposal when possible

## Security & Best Practices

### Execution Policy
- Never use `-ExecutionPolicy Bypass` in production scripts
- Document execution policy requirements in script headers
- Use `Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope Process -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned` for temporary changes

### File Operations
- Always validate file paths with `Test-Path` before operations
- Use `Join-Path` for path construction, never string concatenation
- Sanitize user input for file operations
- Use `-Force` parameter carefully and document why

### Variable Naming
- Use descriptive variable names: `$iconFiles` not `$files`
- Use PascalCase for parameters: `$IconSize` not `$iconsize`
- Use camelCase for local variables: `$createdCount` not `$CreatedCount`
- Avoid single-letter variables except in loops: `$i`, `$j`

### Script Structure
- Include comprehensive parameter help in script header
- Use `#Requires -Version 5.1` for version requirements
- Include `#Requires -Assembly System.Drawing` for .NET dependencies
- Document all functions with proper help comments

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

### Syntax Errors
- Never use `==` for comparison, use `-eq`
- Use `-ne` for not equal, not `!=`
- Use `-and`, `-or` for logical operations, not `&&`, `||`
- Use `$true`, `$false` for boolean values, not `true`, `false`

### Array Operations
- Use `+=` for array concatenation: `$array += $item`
- Use `@()` for empty arrays, not `[]`
- Use `$array.Count` for length, not `$array.Length`
- Use `$array -contains $item` for membership testing

### String Operations
- Use `"$variable"` for string interpolation, not `'$variable'`
- Use `-join` for array joining: `$array -join ','`
- Use `-split` for string splitting: `$string -split ','`
- Use `-replace` for regex replacement: `$string -replace 'pattern', 'replacement'`

### File Operations
- Use `Get-ChildItem` with `-Filter` parameter for file filtering
- Use `-Recurse` for recursive operations
- Use `-Force` to include hidden files
- Use `-ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` for non-critical file operations

## Performance Standards

### Memory Management
- Use `[System.GC]::Collect()` after large operations
- Dispose of large objects immediately after use
- Use `Measure-Object` to monitor memory usage
- Avoid creating large arrays in loops

### Execution Efficiency
- Use `Where-Object` for filtering instead of loops when possible
- Use `ForEach-Object` for pipeline operations
- Use `-Parallel` for independent operations when available
- Cache frequently used values in variables

## Documentation Requirements

### Script Headers
```powershell
# ScriptName.ps1
# Brief description of script purpose
# Author: Name
# Version: 1.0
# Date: YYYY-MM-DD
# Requires: PowerShell 5.1+, System.Drawing
```

### Function Documentation
```powershell
function New-AtlasJson {
    <#
    .SYNOPSIS
    Creates JSON metadata for icon atlas
    
    .DESCRIPTION
    Generates structured JSON data containing icon positions,
    dimensions, and metadata for sprite sheet atlases.
    
    .PARAMETER IconSize
    Size specification (e.g., "16x16")
    
    .PARAMETER IconFiles
    Array of icon file objects
    
    .EXAMPLE
    New-AtlasJson -IconSize "16x16" -IconFiles $files
    #>
}
```

## Validation Checklist

Before submitting PowerShell code, verify:
- [ ] All functions use approved verbs
- [ ] Parameters have proper validation
- [ ] Error handling covers all failure cases
- [ ] Resources are properly disposed
- [ ] Output is consistent and informative
- [ ] File paths are validated before use
- [ ] Variables use proper naming conventions
- [ ] No hardcoded paths or values
- [ ] Script includes proper documentation
- [ ] No execution policy bypasses
- [ ] All operations have meaningful error messages

## Project-Specific Standards

### Atlas Generation Scripts
- Use `New-AtlasJson`, `New-AtlasCsv`, `New-AtlasXml` for generation functions
- Use `Invoke-IconSizeProcessing` for processing functions
- Always validate JSON structure before saving
- Include file existence checks before operations
- Use consistent naming: `icon_set_{size}_atlas.{ext}`

### Test Scripts
- Use `Test-PipelineStep` for individual test functions
- Include comprehensive error reporting
- Provide clear success/failure indicators
- Use `Write-Status` for consistent output formatting
- Include cleanup functionality with `-Cleanup` parameter

### File Naming Conventions
- Use descriptive names: `Generate-Atlas.ps1`, `Test-Pipeline.ps1`
- Avoid generic names like `script.ps1` or `test.ps1`
- Use kebab-case for multi-word names
- Include purpose in filename when possible